## 1. SERP Intent Analysis

### 1a. Dominant Content Format

The SERP is dominated by **definition + how-to hybrid content**: pages that first define what a short-term lease agreement is, then walk through what it must include, followed by a downloadable template. Seven of the nine retrievable competitor URLs follow this exact structure. The eSign.com and LegalTemplates.net results lead with definitions and clause breakdowns. The iGMS.com and Lodgify.com results add a "why you need one" section. All competitors converge on a listicle-within-a-guide format: a numbered list of clauses embedded inside a longer explanatory article.

**The brightplace article must match this format:** definition-first, then clause-by-clause breakdown, then practical guidance. It should NOT be a pure listicle (no standalone "top 10 clauses" format without framing context). It should NOT be a template-download page (brightplace does not offer document downloads).

The key differentiation opportunity: competitors are almost exclusively writing for **landlords and hosts**. The SERP has a coverage gap for **renters** trying to understand what they are about to sign. brightplace's article targets renters reading before they commit.

